  "prompt": "Is smoking banned in Bhutan?",
  "response": "Yes, smoking is banned in public places in Bhutan. The country is known for its stringent tobacco control laws, which are part of its broader commitment to promoting public health and environmental well-being. The Tobacco Control Act of Bhutan, enacted in 2010, prohibits the sale and distribution of tobacco products and bans smoking in public areas, including government offices, public transport, and educational institutions. \n\nHowever, there are some exceptions. Individuals are allowed to import tobacco for personal use, but they must pay a 100% tax and declare it at customs. Additionally, smoking is permitted in private homes and designated smoking areas, but these are subject to strict regulations.\n\nBhutan's approach to tobacco control is part of its unique philosophy of Gross National Happiness (GNH), which prioritizes the well-being of its citizens over purely economic measures. The ban on smoking in public places aligns with this philosophy by aiming to create a healthier and more harmonious society.",
